Exercise 1 (62 points). Consider the ChickWeight data set that is built into base R. Notice from the code book, weight and Time are quantitative variables while Chick and Diet are categorical variables.

  1. (10 points) Create a tibble chicks that contains the data fromChickWeightwith the following changes: (i) weight is renamed Mass, (ii) Diet becomes a factor variable, (iii) the Chick variable is removed, and (iv) a new variable weeks contains the time in units of weeks. Obtain the five cases of chicks with the largest mass.

    chicks = ChickWeight %>% transmute(mass = weight, time = Time, diet = as.factor(Diet), weeks = floor(Time/7))

  2. (10 points) Obtain the linear model Mass ~ Time - 1. Explicitly state the best fit formula. Interpret the single coefficient. State the residual standard error (with units) and the proportion of the variation in mass that is explained by the model.

    chickmodel1 = lm(mass ~ time - 1, chicks)
summary(chickmodel1)

    The best fit formula is mass (g) = 10.63 * time (days), meaning that a chick grows by 10.63 grams every day. The RSE is 41.55 grams and 91.32% of the variation in mass is explained by this model.

  3. (10 points) Obtain the linear model Mass ~ Diet:Time - 1. Interpret the obtained coefficients. State the residual standard error (with units) and the proportion of the variation in mass that is explained by the model.

    chickmodel2 = lm(mass ~ diet:time - 1, chicks)
summary(chickmodel2)

    According to this model, chicks on diet 1 gain about 8.9 grams per day, chicks on diet 2 gain about 10.5 grams per day, chicks on diet 3 gain about 12.6 grams per day, and chicks on diet 4 gain about 11.8 grams per day.

    The RSE is 37.17 grams and 93.05% of the variation in mass is explained by this model.

  4. (10 points) Obtain a scatter plot of Mass vs.Time grouped by Diet (use color or shape to display the groups) with lines showing the model obtained in part (c). Include appropriate labels for the axes.

    chicks %>% ggplot(aes(x = time, y = mass, color = diet)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6) +
  geom_lm() +
  scale_color_viridis(discrete = TRUE) +
  xlab('mass (g)') +
  ylab('time (days)')

  5. (2 points) Based on this data, which diet would be best for a chicken farmer?

    Allow me to depart from the data for a moment and point out that it seems rather impossible to determine what is best based on weight alone. We dont know the cost of any of these feeds per chick per day, or if the feed type affects mean quality. It doesnt matter how much meat is on the bird if none of it is particularly good.

    That said, according to chickmodel2, diet 3 offers the highest rate of change for chicks mass. If the goal is to increase the chicks mass as fast as possible, then diet 3 would accomplish that task most effectively. However, since we havent learned how to do f-tests yet, I cant say for sure if diet actually has a clear impact on mass. Since the values of R-squared are so close, its just really hard to say if it matters at all.

  6. (10 points) Obtain the sample size, mean, standard deviation, and 95% coverage interval mass for the chicks at 10 days. In addition to the computation, state your answers in a sentence with appropriate precision and units.

    chicks10 = chicks %>% filter(time == 10)
chicks10 %>% summarise(n = n(), mean = mean(mass), sd = sd(mass), lower = quantile(mass, 0.025), upper = quantile(mass, 0.975))

    There were 49 chicks whose masses were measured at ten days old. Their masses had a mean of 107.8 grams and a standard deviation of 24.99 grams, and 95% of the masses fell between 67.2 grams and 157.8 grams.

  7. (10 points) Use resampling to obtain a 95% confidence interval for the mean mass of chicks at 10 days. In addition to the computation, state your answer in a sentence with appropriate precision and units.

    rmean = function(n0) {
  chicks10 %>%
    slice_sample(n = n0, replace = TRUE) %>% 
    summarise(mean = mean(mass))
}

x = tibble(mean = NULL)
for (i in 1:1000) {
  x = bind_rows(x, rmean(200))
}
x %>% summarise(quantile(mean, 0.025), quantile(mean, 0.975))

    With 95% confidence, the true mean weight of a ten-day-old chick is 107.9 \(\pm\) 3.4 grams.

Exercise 2 (25 points). Each row in HousmanGrades.csv file corresponds to a student taking a course from David Housman at Goshen College. Students who received CR, NC, or I grades were excluded. Some students took more than one course from David Housman and so appear in multiple rows. The Course column contains an identifier for the course (e.g., MA321 is Math 321 Differential Equations). The Time column contains an identifier for the term in which the course was taken (e.g., 2016-2017 Fall is the Fall semester of the 2016-2017 academic year, and 1998 MIS-98L is a special term for a cohort of degree completion students). The Grade column contains the letter grade received by the student in the given course during the given term.

  1. (4 points) Read the data from the file into a data frame or tibble. How many student-course cases are in the data set?

    HousmanGrades <- read.csv("~/Desktop/HousmanGrades.csv")
nrow(HousmanGrades)
    ## [1] 2264

  2. (2 points) Obtain the number of different courses that David Housman has taught at Goshen College (for which at least one student received a standard letter grade).

    unique(HousmanGrades$Course) %>% length()
    ## [1] 54

  3. (4 points) Obtain the absolute and relative frequencies of the courses of the five most taken courses.

    HousmanGrades %>% count(Course) %>% slice_max(n, n = 5) %>% mutate(rel = round(n/2264, 2))

  4. (6 points) Obtain a bar chart of the frequency of each grade given by David Housman. For full credit, the letter grades should appear in the best-to-worst order A, A-, B+, B, B-, C+, C, C-, D+, D, F. One approach to accomplish this is to use the factor command inside a mutate command. The point of this exercise is to see if you can figure out how to do this by reading the documentation (the help tab in RStudio)

    grade_order = c('A','A-','B+','B','B-','C+','C','C-','D+','D','F')
HousmanGrades %>% mutate(Grade = ordered(HousmanGrades$Grade, levels = grade_order)) %>% ggplot(aes(x = Grade, fill = Grade)) +
  geom_bar(show.legend = FALSE) +
  scale_fill_viridis(discrete = TRUE, option = 'plasma')

  5. (3 points) Create a new column QPts that recodes letter grades by their equivalent quality points: A becomes 4.0, A- becomes 3.7, B+ becomes 3.3, and so forth.

    HousmanGrades %>% mutate(QPts = recode_factor(HousmanGrades$Grade, 'A' = 4.0, 'A-' = 3.7, 'B+' = 3.3, 'B' = 3.0, 'B-' = 2.7, 'C+' = 2.3, 'C' = 2.0, 'C-' = 1.7, 'D+' = 1.3, 'D' = 1.0, 'F' = 0))

  6. (3 points) Obtain a density plot of quality points.

    HousmanGrades %>% mutate(QPts = recode(HousmanGrades$Grade, 'A' = 4.0, 'A-' = 3.7, 'B+' = 3.3, 'B' = 3.0, 'B-' = 2.7, 'C+' = 2.3, 'C' = 2.0, 'C-' = 1.7, 'D+' = 1.3, 'D' = 1.0, 'F' = 0)) %>% ggplot(aes(x = QPts)) +
  geom_density()

  7. (3 points) In what way(s) are the graphs in parts (f) and (d) similar to and different from a normal distribution?

    Theyre similar in that there appears to be a bell curve-esque shape covering each letter except F (i.e., one going from C+ to C- and centered at C), but different in that there are multiple such curves across the data whereas in a normal distribution we would expect only one. Each separate curve also seems to be skewed, mostly toward the positive.
